(28, 'SOLAR_FIELDS', 'This is lamenting about the chore requirements some Airbnb’s instill, which I haven’t seen as much, but a recent discovery I made that is helpful to get around the other annoyance (ridiculous cleaning fees) hinted at in the article: in NL it’s illegal to unbundle price and cleaning fees, so if you browse with a Dutch VPN you get a map with both price and cleaning included, unlike in the States: <a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;news.ycombinator.com&#x2F;item?id=32780998#32786503\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;news.ycombinator.com&#x2F;item?id=32780998#32786503</a>', 32879111, 32879503, '2022-09-17 00:00:00', 0),
(29, 'julianlam', '&gt; Last month, Amanda Morari spent her sister’s bachelorette weekend at a lakefront cottage in Ontario province.<p>As a Canadian it felt a little weird seeing &quot;province&quot; tacked on to the end of Ontario (and Quebec, earlier on in the article). Is this an Americanism, and why?<p>I get that there is Washington State and Washington, DC, but there&#x27;s only one Texas, one Connecticut, one North Dakota...<p>No Canadian I know calls it Ontario province or Yukon territory (though I suppose the NWT is the lone exception.)', 32879111, 32879448, '2022-09-17 00:00:00', 0),
